Month = {{MAY 29}},
Abstract = {{Within modern gymnosperms, conifers and Ginkgo are exclusively wind
   pollinated whereas many gnetaleans and cycads are insect pollinated. For
   cycads, thrips are specialized pollinators. We report such a specialized
   pollination mode from Early Cretaceous amber of Spain, wherein four
   female thrips representing a genus and two species in the family
   Melanthripidae were covered by abundant Cycadopites pollen grains. These
   females bear unique ring setae interpreted as specialized structures for
   pollen grain collection, functionally equivalent to the hook-tipped
   sensilla and plumose setae on the bodies of bees. The most parsimonious
   explanation for this structure is parental food provisioning for larvae,
   indicating subsociality. This association provides direct evidence of
   specialized collection and transportation of pollen grains and likely
   gymnosperm pollination by 110-105 million years ago, possibly
   considerably earlier.}},
